@Gankro 

> @aturon: We have a few collections which can't "properly" support reserve_exact due to power_of_two capacity shenanigans. Should they offer `reserve_exact` at all then? It seems a bit odd to offer it, but at the same time _not_ offering it is exposing non-fundamental implementation details as part of the public API. It doesn't strictly _hurt_ to offer reserve_exact as a synonym for reserve in these cases, especially since the new documented/tested semantics of these methods basically allows them to do the exact same thing. The caller can't expect anything else.

I think it's fine to offer `reserve_exact` for these. We can finesse this in documentation: while `reserve` will try to do something that makes sense for general amortization, `reserve_exact` will _try_ to reserve exactly the additional number of slots specified -- emphasis on _try_.

